text: I'm sick of seeing the same "Remember when Fast and Furious was about racing.." comments doing the rounds. I just wanna tell this...  Remember Tokyo Drift, a movie that was completely about racing? And the fact that the same people complaining now were the same people that hated the movie when it came out?  So what exactly is the problem for all you guys who're complaining?  Besides, no FF movie other than Tokyo Drift was completely about racing. Racing was an element, almost a front for Dom and his crew whose real job is boosting trucks in the first FF movie, which means they were street racers 14 YEARS AGO.. And Brian joined the racing under cover to find out who the real culprits were.  So yeah, FF wasn't completely about racing.  Ever since Fast 4, the characters evolved, their lives changed, time's passing and they're getting older. Deal with it. :)  Besides, not a single movie has been without fast cars and chases. I don't get what your problem is.

text: This movie is going to be amazing and emotional!  There's something I really want to know, and it's the 'story' of the Plymouth Road Runner... So the grey Road Runner appears here in the ending of Tokyo Drift, and Dom says to Sean 'I won it from my friend Han a few years ago' . In Fast & Furious (2009)  the car appears again, and is driven by Letty this time until she has the accident where she gets side-kicked by Fenix. Following the flip over the car explodes...   Nowadays we all know (the real fans at least know it) that Tokyo Drift takes part after Fast & Furious 6 and basically at the same time time as Furious 7 (takes part in the beginning of Furious 7 I think, the part where Han dies)  The ending of Tokyo Drift reappears in Furious 7, so we can see the grey Road Runner...  So my question is:  Where did Letty get the Road Runner? and where did Dom get the Road Runner, which is the same as Letty had in Fast & Furious (2009) and exploded?  I mean if the exact storyline is that Fast & Furious (2009) occurs before Tokyo Drift...  Also in Furious 7 Dom has a Road Runner again, but this time it has another look, Fire Red paint job, black hood, chrome Muscle car style wheels!

text: A tribute to Brian and Dom and their Fast & Furious Journey…   Back in the day, it was 2001 A family drove cars to have a bit of fun Their world was wild, furious and fast And we all fell in love with a special cast One man a rebel, the other from law Crossed paths on the street, then fought the same war Together they drove, side by side And formed a friendship, to become a long ride Then parted ways when rules were broken As enemies became friends without a word spoken Around each other they took to the road Each of them carting their own heavy load Running away from mistakes of the past To avoid getting caught they had to move fast But when fate brought them back together again And thrust them both into the lions den To face battle with foes powerful and strong And actions were needed, despite right or wrong Loved ones were lost, families were made These friends, now brothers, from the world they’d fade Slipping deeper down into the world of under Where the cars drove faster, and loud as thunder Until a new man of the law said the hunt was on To bring these fugitives down until he had won But unlikely as it seemed to all involved Teaming up was how their problems were solved And a new crew was formed to pull off the jobs Toretto, O’Conner and Special Agent Hobbs The stakes got higher, the roads opened wide Wars fought on the street, a destruction tide And friends turned brothers became family To bring us Furious 7, we just can’t wait to see

text: Saw the movie last night on Times Square. I didn't like it at all. I liked all of the other movies but not this one. I think the problem with this movie is that after Paul Walker died, they scrambled to rewrite it, and you can tell they didn't do a very good job with the writing. The movie was basically a bunch of unnecessary massive stunts, crashes, and explosions, none of which made any sense. For example, flying your car from building to building just to elude a couple of security guards. Really? Why not just jump out of the car and beat them up like you normally do. Or flying your car off the roof of a building to crash it into a helicopter. So Dom Torretto, what do you plan to do after you actually crash your vehicle into the helicopter. And too much martial arts. I don't mind the hand-to-hand fighting but it just went on and on and on that it dragged. I didn't know if I was watching a martial arts flick or a car movie. And it was way too geeky. I don't mind geek, but at least make the geeky stuff realistic. And most of the major stunts of the movie revolved around getting access to a computer chip, which they ultimately never took advantage of. And if that wasn't stupid, the fact that Jason Statham kept mysteriously appearing in places that he should have had no knowledge about made the movie super and utterly ridiculous. I get the fact that Statham found them at Han's funeral, but how did he know to find them on the hijacking mission in the middle of nowhere, and not only that be in the exact spot where everything was going down? Wasn't that supposed to be a secret mission? And how did Statham know to show up at the billionaire party in Abu Dhabi? Is there a Mole on Toretto's team? Or was Statham also looking for the computer chip? NONE of this was discussed. It was just "oh, there's Statham, let's fight him", instead of "how the hell did he know how to get here". Talk about plot holes. And they just totally abandoned the whole Race Wars theme with the crowd of hot girls, fancy cars, and cheering spectators - except for one little 2 minute scene in the beginning. It was like the producers threw in real quick just for the heck of it, and then added a cameo of Iggy Azalea to make you forget how they totally abandoned that aspect of the franchise. nd cheering crowd is really what made the franchise. The best part of the movie for me was when they parachuted their cars out of the plane and the drove off on the road and got in formation to get that bus. That was SOOOOO episode 1!!!!! The only thing that messed up the scene was Jason Statham mysteriously popping up out of nowhere in a vehicle, like really? How did you know they were there? That was a secret mission in a heavily guarded area, which is why they had to parachute in. How did YOU get it? They did a bad job with this movie.

text: Assisti o Fast 7 e... pra mim perdeu a graça. Só um monte de situações muito fora da realidade demais. O filme ficou sem conteúdo. Tem drone e helicóptero de guerra contra carros. Foi excesso de violência, quase nada de texto, festival de efeitos especiais. Um cem número de vezes eles são salvos do nada, isso compete com o excesso de bizarrice do filme. Parece que quem escreveu não tava nem aí com o público, o diretor e a edição do filme ficaram PÉSSIMAS.  Teve pontos bons como o Roman Pierce que tirou umas gargalhadas, a luta com a Ronda, e a homenagem ao Paul. Fora isso... Decepção, parecia que eles tinham vergonha do passado que foi a verdadeira estória do F&F. A gente adora carros e corridas e não vai ao cinema pra ver DRONES, cenas de "james Bond". Pra mim consertar a mega cagada cinematográfica que foi esse filme vai ser MUIITO DIFÍCIL. A cena da letty recuperando a memória é RIDÍCULA e dura menos de 1 minuto. Parece que Paul W. vai fazer mais falta do que eu achava. Pra mim o F&F acaba no 6 e vai ser impossível consertar a M.. gigante que foi esse conteúdo. Esse filme impacta, mas morre na praia pq. é só efeitos especiais e violência 97% do tempo... Resumindo pra mim foi uma BOSTA e sei que ainda tem várias continuações agendadas que não pretendo assistir nem o 7,8,9, 10, ou o que vier.

text: I have never seen such a bad movie get this rating on metacritic(6/10). This movie is amazingly awful. It makes no sense, the acting is terrible, the dialogue is terrible, and the action is surprisingly terrible (shaky-cam, lack of focus, effects over actual choreography) as well. It really is a shame to waste money on making or seeing this movie.   Amazing foibles: Half CG Paul Walker is like watching a Japanese "real doll" placed in an action movie (sorry Paul). The camera angles and dialogue surrounding him is so surreal. I was so distracted by the efforts to pretend he was alive for the whole movie that I couldn't focus on the movie, not that you need to focus to watch this nonsense. Also, the plot makes no sense whatsoever. I can't even describe it. They try to find a device to just track down Jason Statham, yet he finds the crew at every other scene. Also, for some reason they need to drive cars out of a plane to reach a bus transport, yet Jason Statham manages to be at the same place without falling out of plane. Why did they need to do it? They didn't. This whole movie did not need to happen.   Vin Diesel is old, and just rambles on about family and the streets and other nonsense. HE WEARS A WHITE CUT OFF TO HIS OWN WEDDING. Classic Vin...   Also, they go to Tokyo as if there is no time interruption from Tokyo drift, yet the Tokyo drift actor is 10 years older than he was in that movie. They really think the audience is dumb as a couch.   This movie is just a series of scenes of people lining up for the camera and cars doing the same.

You need to save those perfect one liners for important places in your films, not base the entire movie dialog on them, Blah Blah Blah boring writing and directing.  It's not the actors fault, I'll give them that much, but I do wish they would stand up and recognize a horrible script when they read one.
